  apis-server

# Design (and limitations)
The API server (apis.go) uses a DB struct from dbutil.go to interact directly with a SQLite
database (updater.db) via the github.com/mattn/go-sqlite3 driver. SQLite is a file-based,
embedded database, accessed via local file operations (e.g., /app/updater.db in the Docker
container). The Server struct holds a *DB reference, and methods like ValidateAPIKey,
GetOrInsertTenant, etc., execute SQL queries directly. This works well for single-node,
low-to-moderate load scenarios, as SQLite is lightweight, serverless, and supports concurrent
reads with serialized writes.

1) The API server opens a SQLite connection to updater.db using sql.Open("sqlite3", dbPath).
2) Queries are executed directly via the DB struct’s methods (e.g., db.QueryRow, db.Exec).
3) SQLite handles file-level locking for concurrency (WAL mode supports multiple readers and one writer).
